{
  "text": "Magnesium and its alloys are attractive materials for a wide range of applications in such demanding fields as transportation, electronics or aerospace [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . This is due to superior attributes such as low density, high thermal conductivity, and ease of manufacturing by conventional processes. Currently, most of the magnesium alloy usage in industry is limited to die-cast components [CITATION_3] . In the future, the increasing demand for large-scale applications of wrought Mg alloy products, such as extruded profiles, rolled sheets and forgings, will determine the development of Mg alloys. The wrought Mg alloys offer better mechanical properties in comparison to cast Mg alloys because of the pronounced grain refinement without pores and uniform composition distribution after the deformation process [CITATION_4] . However, the high friction between the workpiece and tool steel during the forming process cannot be avoided, thus resulting in relatively short tool life, high energy consumption and poor-quality products [CITATION_5] 6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "136339079",
